column43: Spill Clean UP and Filter Maintenance
column168: While performing a site walk at Veolia's 10 day intransit facility, the Veolia General Manager noticed  a small puddle of red liquid on the ground under one of the intransit trailers. Upon offloading the  trailer, the leaking drum was identified and overpacked. The leaked material inside the trailer and  on the ground was remediated using spill dry.  All debris and PPE were placed in a container for  proper disposal. The trailer was reloaded and the overpacked container was placed on the rear of  the trailer.  The package failure was the result of a hole in the bottom of the container. Veolia  witnessed liquid dripping out of the hole and flowing onto the floor of the trailer. Veolia believes that the hole may have come from gravel. The drums were shipped from a pipeline company and may have been stored on gravel prior to being loaded on the truck.  The gravel could have worn a hole  in the bottom of the drum. There is also a chance that the container was damaged before it was  used for its current purpose.
column169: Veolia overpacked the container to ensure that it would not leak as it continues in transportation to the  final disposal site. Veolia has also contact the broker that provided the container to express concern with the condition of the container.  Veolia also spoke with the field office that loaded the trailer.  The  container should have been properly inspected by both parties prior to leaving the original shipper's  location.  Veolia's team will be retrained on what to look for when loading and unloading containers. The broker was asked to be more diligent about container inspections before they bring the material to a Veolia site.

At 16:00est Ken Bristow from Superior Carriers called ERTS to report a 40 gallon release of Ferric sulfate. The caller stated the release occurred while offloading causing 40 gallons to released onto a concrete pad. The release occurred at 10516 Gordon Road, Spotsylvania, VA at the County of Spotsylvania water treatment facility. No drains, soils or waterways were impacted. First Call Environmental arrived on site and located the release. Confirmed 30 gallons of Ferric Sulfate released in a 30' x 90' area on the parking lot asphalt when the Superior Carriers tanker was off loading into the storage facility and the connection hose provided by the customer broke. First Call will neutralize the release once they pH test the area and utilize absorbents. First Call has the release to a neutral 6. First Call is complete with the cleanup at this time. The standing liquid was absorbed with absorbents, booms and shoveled into 8-55 gallon poly drums.The entire area is neutralized and facility personnel were happy with the cleanup. First Call departed site with the waste.

It is a flammable liquid per IATA/ICAO standards. As the shipper had not offered the shipment with any DG markings, DG labels nor a shipper's declaration it's undeclared/hidden DG. The FAA was notified via email and photos were sent. FAA PHI Steven Redeker sent an email that we could release the shipment to the customer.

FULLY LABELED HAZ-MAT SHIPMENT WAS DISCOVERED WET IN APPEARANCE AT DOOR 4 BY THE SUPERVISOR IN UNLOAD-A. WITHOUT TOUCHING THE PKG SHE EVACUATED THE AREA AND CONTACTED DMP. A RESPONDER ARRIVED WITHIN A FEW MINUTES, DONNING THE PROPER PPE. THERE WAS NO INTERNAL PACKING MATERIAL AND THE OUTER CARTON WAS A DOUBLEWALL FIBERBOARD BOX, RATED AT 61 A LBS/IN EDGE CRUSH TEST (ECT).
I DISCOVERED THE PACKAGE AT END OF BLUE BELT WHICH WAS BROUGHT IN EARLIER BY A PACKAGE DRIVER.

column168: On November 7, 2019, a tractor-trailer operated by R+L Carriers, Inc. (RLC) was discovered to have a cargo leak at 4426 Hunt Ave. in St. Louis, MO. As a result of the leak, one(1) 55-gallon drum leaked approximately 1.5 gallons of adhesive containing fiammable liquid to the trailer interior At approximately 2:30 p.m. CST, a representative with RLC retained Cura Emergency Services, L.C. (CES) to manage the environmental cleanup of the site. Based on the available information, the CES incident manager dispatched a crew from Environmental Management Alternatives (EMA) to assess and remediate the site. EMA crews entered the trailer, shifted materials in trailer to gain access, and noted that a 55-gallon drum of adhesive had released 1- 1.5 gallons from the bung due to an unsecured bung cap. EMA cleaned glue impacted trailer freight with parts cleaner, then cleaned trailer floor with parts cleaner. All areas were cleaned with absorbent rags. All cleanup waste was collected and containerized in one(1) 55-gallon drum for disposal. EMA re-secured the bung cap and trailer freight. Once the remediation was complete, EMA secured the scene and demobilized.

column168: On 11/3/19 at approximately 12:24 PST, a BNSF switchman noticed the GBRX 705746 leaking a minor amount of liquid from the manway.  The car was isolated and notifications were made.  BNSF Hazmat responders arrived to the car and performed an assessment.  All leaked ethanol evaporated from the car body.  One manway swingbolt was found to be less than tool tight near the manway hinge.  Responders removed the shipper's load seal from the manway swingbolt and opened the manway to inspect the gasket and sealing surface.  The hard lid gasket appeared to be in fair condition but was replaced with a nozzle gasket as a precaution and the lid was resecured.  All other fittings and appliances on the car were inspected.  No remediation was necessary as all ethanol had evaporated.  The car was then released for continued movement in transportation.

column168: On November 21, 2019, at 0149 ET, ERTS was contacted by XPO Logistics Terminal XMI regarding a cargo release.  It was reported that due to improper loading, (1) 55-gallon poly drum of Potassium Hydroxide (Potassium hydroxide, solution, UN1814) was damaged, releasing approximately 3 gallons of product on to a 6' by 6' area of the trailer floor.    A contractor was dispatched to clean up the release using absorbents, neutralizer and the proper PPE.  The damaged drum, spent absorbents and all other debris were containerized in (1) 95-gallon poly drum and (2) 55-gallon poly drums.  The waste drums were then staged onsite at OS&D for terminal personnel to manage.

On November 20, 2019, at 1734 ET, ERTS was contacted by XPO Logistics Terminal XWC regarding a cargo release.  It was reported that due to a forklift accident, (1) 55-gallon metal drum of FS-63 Fluorosurfactant (Flammable liquid, n.o.s., UN1993) was punctured, releasing an unknown amount of product container to the top of the drum.  A contractor was dispatched to clean up the release with absorbents and the proper PPE.  The damaged drum, spent absorbents and all other debris were containerized in (2) 85-gallon metal drums and (2) 55-gallon metal drums.  The waste drums were then staged onsite at OS&D for terminal personnel to manage.

On November 25, 2019, at 2234 ET, ERTS was contacted by XPO Logistics Terminal LHO regarding a cargo release.  It was reported that due to a forklift accident, (1) 275-gallon poly tote of ChemTreat CL2874 (Sodium hydroxide, solution, UN1824) was punctured, releasing approximately 15 gallons of product on to a 3' by 5' area of both the dock and trailer floors.  A contractor was dispatched to clean up the release using absorbents and the proper PPE.  The remaining product in the damaged tote, as well as all other waste debris generated were containerized in (3) 55-gallon poly drums.  The damaged tote (empty) was staged on the dock to be returned to the original shipper.  The waste drums were then staged onsite at OS&D for terminal personnel to manage.

column168: ON NOVEMBER 9TH 2019, A SEMI TRUCK TANKER OPERATED BY ENERGY DISPATCH, WAS DELIVERING DIESEL FUEL INTO AN UNDER GROUND STORAGE TANK AT RACETRAC LOCATION #243 1975 SW RAILROAD AVENUE. THE DELIVERY DRIVER FILLED 2 TANKS AT THE LOCATION. BOTH TANKS HAD MORE THAN ENOUGH ULLAGE TO HOLD THE DELIVERED GALLONS ACCORDING TO THE AUTOMATIC TANK GUAGES THAT WERE UTILIZED FOR THIS TRANSFER. FOR UNKNOWN REASONS, TANK #2'S TANK GUAGE WAS GIVING INCORRECT INFORMATION, AND SUBSEQUENTLY SAID TANK WAS OVERFILLED. APPROXIMATELY 50 GALLONS OF FUEL LEAKED OUT ONTO THE CONCRETE APRON. THE DELIVERY DRIVER IMMEDIATELY ATTEMPTED TO CONTAIN THE SPILL TO THE IMMEDIATE AREA WITH ABSORBENT PADS, SNAKE AND GRANULAR ABSORBENT MATERIAL. APPROXIMATELY 5 GALLONS OF FUEL DID MANAGE TO LEAK PAST THE DRIVERS EFFORTS TO CONTAIN, AND ENTERED A NEARBY STORM DRAIN CATCH BASIN. ENERGY DISPATCH IMMEDIATELY DISPATCHED A REMEDIATION TEAM TO HANDLE THE CLEAN UP THE FUEL RELEASE.

column168: On 11/12/19 at approximately 12:30 PST, WA UTC Inspector Cal Stocking observed what appeared to be residual product (coal tar pitch) with sheen on the car body and dripping to the ground.  Call immediately reached out to BNSF to inform the RR of the car condition.  BNSF kept the car isolated until an inspection could be performed by Hazmat responders.  NRC Env was contracted to respond and inspect the car.  Upon arrival, responders found that a small amount of product had been released from between the flange underneath the liquid line valve.  All 4 nuts on this flange were less than hand tight and easily moved.  Responders secured the valve by tool tightening the valve and cleaning residual coal tar pitch from the valve housing and car body.  A small amount of impacted ballast was removed and placed into a waste container for appropriate disposal.  On 11/13/19, Cal Stocking approved movement of the car to destination without an OTMA.  The short move to Intalco was made on 11/22/19.  The car lessee (Ruetgers) will apply OTMA to move the car to a location to have a bubble leak test performed.

column168: IT WAS REPORTED THAT TANK CAR UTLX 956629 WAS LEAKING FROM ONE OF THE TOP VALVES AT 06:00. OUR IMMEDIATE ACTION WAS TO TURN OFF ALL HEAT SOURCES AS THE CAR WAS A PROPANE RESIDUE AND REACHED OUT TO MARKWEST WHO THE CAR IS CONSIGNED TO. THEY SENT THEIR PLANT SUPERVISOR OUT TO INVESTIGATE AND FIX THE LEAK. ONCE SHAWN FROM MARKWEST ARRIVED HE QUICKLY FOUND THAT THE VAPOR LINE VALVE WAS NOT FULLY CLOSED AND THAT ALL THE PLUGS WHERE NOT TOOL TIGHT. HE THEN CLOSED THE VALVE, TIGHTENED ALL PLUGS AND CHECKED FOR LEAKS VERIFYING THAT THE CAR WAS OK FOR SHIPMENT AGAIN.
column169: OUR PLAN IS TO REACH OUT TO THE SHIPPER OF THIS CAR TO ENSURE THAT PROPER INSPECTION PROCEDURES ARE IN PLACE TO ENSURE THAT ALL CARS ARE IN PROPER CONDITION FOR TRANSPORTATION BEFORE OFFERING TO CARRIERS.

column168: ON 11/5/2019 AT ~10:45 AM, AN SMS CREW (A CONTRACT SHORTLINE RAIL HANDLER FOR EAGLE POINT) ATTEMPTED TO CONNECT RAILCARS TO THE EAGLES POINT OFFLOAD RACK. WHILE FOLLOWING THE STANDARD PROCEDURES FOR CONNECTING THE RAILCAR, THE SMS CREW UNSCREWED THE OFFLOAD CAP FROM BOTTOM OF RAILCAR TEIX 173010. NATURAL GASOLINE BEGAN POURING OUT OF THE RAILCAR. THE RELEASE LASTED APPROX 20 MINUTES. EAGLE POINT OPERATORS WERE ABLE TO TEMPORARILY CONNECT A VACUUM TRUCK TO THE TOP OF THE RAIL CAR AND CREATE A SUCTION IN ORDER TO STOP THE FLOW AND REINSTALL THE CAP. IT WAS DETERMINED THAT 143 BBLS (6,006 GALLONS) OF PRODUCT WAS RELEASED INTO SECONDARY CONTAINMENT FOR THE RAIL RACK.
column169: EAGLE POINT RECEIVED THE RAILCAR WITH HE VALVE APPEARING TO BE CLOSED AS EVIDENCE BY THE VALVE POSITION AND THE TWO PINS THAT WERE SEALED CLOSED. FURTHER INSPECTION POST-INCIDENT INDICATES THE VALVE WAS PREVIOUSLY FORCED CLOSED. AS A RESULT, THE MECHANISM THAT ATTACHES THE VALVE HANDLE TO THE VALVE BODY WAS SHEARED AND BOV (BOTTOM OUTLET VALVE) WAS ~50% OPEN.  THE BOV IN QUESTION IS A RELATIVELY UNIQUE STYLE. WE'VE RETRAINED OUR OPERATORS AT EAGLE POINT REGARDING THE "LESSONS LEARNED" FROM THIS INCIDENT AND THE PROPER OPERATION OF THE BOV. WE'VE ALSO SHARED THE LESSON LEARNED INTERNALLY WITHIN OUR COMPANY AND CENTENNIAL. THIS INCIDENT ALSO REITERATES THE IMPORTANCE OF CHECKING THE BOV AT THE ORIGIN PRIOR TO LOADING A RAILCAR.

HE SOLIDIFIED LEAKING PRODUCT OF THE UNDECLARED SHIPMENT WITH CLAY-BASED ABSORBENT MATERIAL, TAPED BAG CLOSED AND WALKED AWAY. A PRELOADER IN THE AREA SAW SMOKE COMING FROM THE BAG IN THE SPILL TRAY AND NOTIFIED THE SAFETY SUPERVISOR. THE SAFETY SUPERVISOR INSTRUCTED THE RESPONDER TO NOTIFY MANAGER TO CALL PE. THE SAFETY SUPERVISOR CALLED THE PE SPILL COORDINATOR FOR AN OUTSIDE CONTRACTOR. OUTSIDE CONTRACTOR PROCESSED THE SOLIDIFIED AND THE REMAINING PRODUCT.

BUCKET WAS FOUND IN THE UNLOAD THAT WAS DAMAGED TO SIDE. UPON DAMAGE INSPECTION, BUCKET WAS FOUND TO CONTAIN VARIOUS MISCELLANEOUS AMMUNITION CARTRIDGES (BULLETS) IN AN UNMARKED RECEPTACLE. HAZMAT HELP DESK WAS CONTACTED AND WE WERE INSTRUCTED TO HOLD SHIPMENT AS A POSSIBLE UNDECLARED SHIPMENT OF HAZARDOUS GOODS.

A LEAKING PACKAGE WAS RESPONDED TO IN THE SOUTH PRIMARY. ONCE THE PACKAGE WAS BEING PROCESSED IN THE DMP AREA THE INNER CARTONS REVIELED DOT CORROSIVE 8 DIAMOND LABELS. ALL LIQUID WAS SOLIDIFIED AND NOTHING WAS RETURNED TO THE SHIPPER.
UNDECLARED HAZARDOUS MATERIAL DISCOVERED DURING PACKAGE AUDIT. NO MARKS OR LABELS ON OUTER CARTON. THIS SHIPMENT HAS NOT BEEN ACCEPTED FOR AIR OR TRANSPORTED IN THE AIR BY UNITED PARCEL SERVICE CO.

column168: On November 28, 2019, at 0448 ET, ERTS was contacted by XPO Logistics Terminal XKC regarding a cargo release.  It was reported that due to improper loading, (1) 5-gallon metal drum of Polane S Plus Polyurethane Enamel (Paint, flammable, UN1263) was damaged, releasing approximately 5 gallons of product on to the trailer floor.  After reviewing the SDS with the caller, terminal personnel stated that they felt comfortable cleaning up the release with absorbents and the proper PPE.  The damaged drum, spent absorbents and all other debris were containerized in (1) 55-gallon metal drum which was then staged onsite at OS&D for terminal personnel to manage.

column169: Training will be provided to ensure that packages are not overfilled and that sufficient absorbent material be used to prevent movement of packages and absorb any leaking material.

Following a site assessment, HE personnel observed approximately less-than-one(<1) gallon of corrosive liquid released to the concrete and wooden pallet surface. All spent absorbents and corrosive liquid impacted pallet debris were collected and containerized into one(1) 5-gallon plastic pale for transport and disposal. RLC advised CES that the punctured jug was to be left on-site in the care of RLC personnel. HE patched the hole on the punctured jug, secured the site, and demobilized, noting no further actions required.

column168: On November 21, 2019, at approximately 11:30 AM CST, R+L Carriers(RLC) terminal staff at the above-referenced location discovered approximately.31 pounds of battery acid released from a battery to the cardboard box and circuit breaker surfaces. At approximately 1:20 PM CST, a representative from RLC retained Cura Emergency Sercices, LC(CES) to manage the environmental remediation of the site on their behalf. Based on the available information, the CES incident manager dispatched a crew from Ancon Services(AS) to assess and remediate the site as necessary. At approximately 3:14 PM CST, a crew from AS arrived on-site. Following a site assessment, AS observed approximately.31 pounds of battery acid released to the cardboard box surface. AS removed the box lid to expose the generator and observed that only the cardboard and circuit breaker were impacted by the release. AS utilized sodium bicarbonate to neutralize all free battery acid product. AS then collected and containerized the battery, circuit breaker, and debris into two(2) 55-gallon drums and one(1) 30-gallon drum for disposal. AS secured the site and demobilized, scheduling to return at a later date to retrieve the waste for disposal after proper profiling could be secured.

column168: PVST driver was on the schedule to load HCl at PVS Transportation and deliver to Great Lakes SteeL PVST driver was hauling trailer 24A in which he had never hauled before. The driver has loaded HCI to GLS one time prior to the spill. When loading trailer 24A, the PVST driver programmed in 9500 gallons in the batch mate when trailer 24A can only hold 9,200 gallons. When the driver returned to the loading rack for the last 1,000 gallons per the loading procedure, he noticed the product was filling to the top and proceeded to hit the emergency stop switch. The emergency stop switch shuts the pump off, however product will still gravity feed from the tank until the manual valve is shut off. PVST driver went to maintenance for assistance which told the driver to close the manual valve; 242 gallons of HCl overfilled trailer 24A.

Update the Tank truck loading terminal procedure which should state to hit the emergency stop button and then close the hand valve.

column168: Delta Air lines was notified November 14, 2019 by local CBP that they confiscated a box of graphene pellets enhanced with Thorium 232 from a passenger’s bag on November 3rd. The passenger was traveling from China with connection to LAS, was interrogated by CBP agents, and released to continue his travels. CBP did not inform us until today, when they mentioned it to a Red Coat on duty at FIS.    They did not allow us to see the package, but we were able to see pictures – it appears to be three sleeves of 30 quarter size pellets each. A CBP agent stated that it alarmed for radioactivity and was therefore detained. The CBP Physicist apparently determined that the material is not allowed to enter the United States and has to be returned to the country of origin.  Destination information not available. Customer has already traveled back home to Shanghai.

column168: AT 13:30 ON NOVEMBER 12, 2019 A KANSAS CITY SOUTHERN RAILWAY (KCS) EMPLOYEE REPORTED AN ODOR COMING FROM THE NORTH END OF THE KCS SHREVEPORT, LA RAILYARD. THE KCS ENVIRONMENTAL & HAZMAT DEPARTMENT MOBILIZED A RAILROAD QUALIFIED RESPONSE CONTRACTOR TO INVESTIGATE.  AFTER INVESTIGATING SEVERAL RAIL CARS, THE ODOR WAS DETERMINED TO BE EMANATING FROM TANK CAR UTLX 76347, A LOADED ASPHALT CAR. APPROXIMATELY 0.5 GALLONS OF LADING WAS OBSERVED TO HAVE LEAKED FROM BETWEEN THE MANWAY LID AND THE MANWAY NOZZLE.  THE CONTRACTOR OPENED THE MANWAY TO CHECK THE GASKET AND DISCOVERED THAT UTLX 76347 WAS OFFERED BY THE SHIPPER WITHOUT A MANWAY GASKET. A NEW MANWAY NOZZLE GASKET WAS INSTALLED. THE MANWAY LID WAS THEN CLOSED AND ALL SWING BOLTS WERE RENDERED TOOL TIGHT. A CHECK OF THE REMAINING SERVICE FITTINGS WAS MADE AND THERE WERE NO DEFICIENCIES. THE CAR WAS SUBSEQUENTLY RELEASE BACK INTO TRANSPORTATION.  FILE NOT: ITEM 19-THE QUANTITY RELEASED WAS ESTIMATED BASED ON THE BEST INFORMATION AVAILABLE AT THE TIME OF FILING. THIS SHIPMENT WAS OFFERED AS A 'BULK' SHIPMENT, AKA ONE CAR LOAD, THEREFORE THE EXACT AMOUNT OFFERED IN THIS PACKAGE IS NOT KNOWN TO THE CARRIER. THIS CARRIER DOES NOT HAVE ACCESS TO MASS BALANCE DATA WHICH CAN EXACTLY QUANTIFY THIS VALUE.

column168: A hawkins driver was attempt to offload a inter-company transfer of 93% sulfuric acid.  Shortly after starting the transfer of acid the driver notice a slight drip come from the clamp holding the bonnet on the Betts Hydrolet valve. Some of the acid got under his face shield and over his chemically resistant coat.
column169: Hawkins retrained the driver upon return not to touch any components used during offloading if they are under pressure.  Hawkins is also is setting a specified orientation for the wing nut on the QRB clamp.   The wing nut should be in the up position on the right side of the valve.  This will help reduce issues by making the up and vertical so that it is appraten that you are tightening instaed of loosening the clamp.

column168: Austin Powder Company (USDOT # 103999) driver was driving a tractor/tanker combination in Marion, IL in early morning November 14, 2019. The road conditions were dry.  The cargo was 43,000 of bulk ammonium nitrate emulsion (UN3375). The vehicle was Westbound on I-24 and attempting to take the I-57 Southbound exit ramp.  The ramp is a relatively sharp curve to the right.  The vehicle took the curve too fast and lost control, overturning onto its driver side, skidding on the road and grass, and finally coming to rest on the right hand side of the road.  A small hole in the head of the tanker caused roughly 35 gallons of product to leak from the package, which was a DOT 407 Specification cargo tank.  First responders arrived at the scene and closed the road.  The driver received a citation in conjunction with the accident (see attachment), and was transported to a local hospital for non-life threatening injuries.  A cleanup crew and wreckers were dispatched to the scene, as well as another company vehicle pulling an empty cargo tank in order to transfer the product.  The damaged vehicle was put upright by the wreckers and the hole in the tank head was plugged.  The product was pumped completely off the damaged vehicle into the other company vehicle.  The damaged vehicle was towed away and has since been deemed  a total loss.  The cleanup crew containerized the product and impacted soil, and removed it from the scene for disposal.  The road was then re-opened.
column169: We feel that the root cause of this accident  based upon our data from the vehicle and the police report is driving too fast for conditions-- specifically negotiating the curve of the road too fast.  The driver in this accident has been terminated.  Included in Austin Powder's training program is instruction on speed control.  This driver had been employed with Austin for roughly 16 months.

column168: On November 8, 2019, at approximately 09:25 a.m. CST tractor-trailer (H00120) operated by R&L Carriers was parked at the loading dock at the above-referenced location when it was discovered that a metal drum was leaking from the lid. As a result of the leak approximately one (1) cup of IP FLEXO SOAP II CONCENTRATE (UN1719) was released to the trailer floor. On November 8, 2019, at approximately 09:35 a.m. CST a representative with R+L Carriers retained Cura Emergency Services, LC(CES) to manage the environmental cleanup of the site. Based on the available information, the CES incident manager dispatched a crew from Hull's Environmental Services to assess and remediate the site. On November 8, 2019, at approximately 01:04 p.m. CST, a crew from Hull's Environmental Services (HES) arrived onsite. Following a site assessment, HES personnel noted approximately 1 cup of IP FLEXO SOAP II CONCENTRATE(UN1719) released to the trailer floor. All IP FLEXO SOAP Il CONCENTRATE(UN1719) impacted material was collected and containerized in 1 x 95-gal overpack drum for internal disposal.

column168: During filling of a railcar at the referenced facility location, operator error led to over-pressurizing of a rail car and subsequent release when the fill line was removed without full closure of the fill port valve. The rail car depressurized with kerosene released to the containment area. Kerosene recovery and minimal impacted soil removal was conducted. Operators exposed to product during depressurization of the rail car were not injured.
column169: Global reviewed loading procedures and lessons learned from the incident with terminal operators. No recommendations are being put forward beyond the control of our individual company.

column168: ON NOVEMBER 12, 2019, AT APPROXIMATELY 6:15 AM CDT, R&L PERSONNEL OBSERVED A LEAK FROM A 55-GALLON DRUM OF UN1210 PRINTER INK. AS A RESULT, APPROXIMATELY 5 GALLONS OF PRINTER INK WAS RELEASED TO THE CONCRETE SURFACE AT DOOR 52. AT APPROXIMATELY 6:33 AM CDT, A REPRESENTATIVE FROM R&L CARRIERS RETAINED CURA EMERGENCY SERVICES, L.C. (CES) TO MANAGE THE ENVIRONMENTAL REMEDIATION OF THE SITE ON THEIR BEHALF. BASED ON THE AVAILABLE INFORMATION, THE CES INCIDENT MANAGER DISPATCHED A CREW FROM MARION ENVIRONMENTAL (ME) TO ASSESS AND REMEDIATE THE SITE AS NECESSARY. AT APPROXIMATELY 7:45 AM CDT, A CREW FROM MARION ENVIRONMENTAL ARRIVED ON-SITE. FOLLOWING A SITE ASSESSMENT, ME NOTED A DAMAGED DRUM OF UN1210 WITH APPROXIMATELY 5 GALLONS RELEASED TO THE TRAILER AND CONCRETE SURFACE. ON-SITE PERSONNEL HAD DEPLOYED GRANULAR ABSORBENTS TO PREVENT FURTHER MIGRATION. ME PERSONNEL DEPLOYED ADDITIONAL GRANULAR TO THE AREA AND WORKED THEM IN WITH HAND TOOLS. ALL PRINTER INK IMPACTED MATERIAL WAS COLLECTED AND CONTAINERIZED INTO ON (1) 55-GALLON DRUM FOR TRANSPORT AND DISPOSAL. THE DAMAGED DRUM WAS PLACED IN A POLY-OVER-PACKED DRUM AND WAS ALSO TAKEN FOR TRANSPORT AND DISPOSAL. HE PERSONNEL NOTED NO FURTHER ACTION REQUIRED ON-SITE AND CREWS DEMOBILIZED.

column25: THE BOEING COMPANY C/O XPO LOGISTICS - SUPPLY CHAIN
column168: ON NOVEMBER 7, 2019, EXPEDITORS-PHL RECEIVED A REQUEST TO PICK UP THREE (3) PIECES OF VARIOUS COMMODITIES GENERALLY DESCRIBED AS AIRCRAFT PARTS ("THE SHIPMENT") FROM THE BOEING COMPANY, INC. ("THE SHIPPER" OR BOEING") FOR AIR TRANSPORTATION SERVICES TO LONDON, UNITED KINGDOM. AT THE TIME OF THE SHIPMENT'S BOOKING, THE SHIPPER'S LETTER OF INSTRUCTION INDICATED THAT THE CARGO DID NOT CONTAIN DG (EXHIBIT A).  EXPEDITORS-PHL ASSIGNED HOUSE AIR WAYBILL NUMBER 4300247489 TO THE SHIPMENT AND PROCEEDED TO MOVE IT VIA GROUND TRANSPORTATION TO EXPEDITORS' NEW YORK FACILITY (EXPEDITORS-JFK") FOR CONSOLIDATION AND EVENTUAL TRANSPORTATION BY AIR TO LONDON.  ON NOVEMBER 8, 2019, EXPEDITORS-JFK TENDERED THE SHIPMENT TO BRITISH AIRWAYS AT THE JOHN F. KENNEDY AIRPORT IN QUEENS, NY ("JFK") FOR AIR TRANSPORTATION TO HEATHROW AIRPORT IN LONDON, UK ("LHR") UNDER MASTER AIR WAYBILL 125-62139070. THE SHIPMENT DEPARTED ON FLIGHT NO. BA114 AT APPROXIMATELY 22:00 EST, ARRIVED IN LHR AND WAS MOVED TO EXPEDITORS' LONDON FACILITY ("EXPEDITORS-LHR") ON NOVEMBER 9, 2019.  ON NOVEMBER 13, 2019, EXPEDITORS-PHL WAS NOTIFED IN WRITING BY BOEING DEFENCE (UK LIMITED ("THE COSIGNEE") THAT AN ITEM WITHIN THE SHIPMENT HAD BEEN SHIPPED AS UNDECLARED DG. EXPEDITOR'S-PHL THEREAFTER RECEIVED UPDATED DOCUMENTATION FROM THE SHIPPER, INCLUDING A SHIPPER'S DECLARATION FOR DANGEROUS GOODS, A MATERIAL SAFETY DATA SHEET AND REVISED COMMERCIAL INVOICE INDICATING THAT THE SHIPMENT CONTAINED DG (EXHIBITS B-D).  THE SHIPMENT WAS PLACED ON HOLD AT EXPEDITORS-LHR FOR INSPECTION AND IT WAS FOUND THAT THE DG ITEM WAS NOT PACKAGED OR LABELED AS REQUIRED UNDER THE 49 CFR OR THE INTERNATIONAL CIVIL AVIATION ORGANIZATION TECHNICAL INSTRUCTIONS FOR THE SAFE TRANSPORT OF DANGEROUS GOODS BY AIR (EXHIBIT E).  ON NOVEMBER 22, 2019, A DG PACKAGING COMPANY WAS DISPATCHED TO EXPEDITORS-LHR TO RE-PACKAGE THE DG ITEM AND BRING IT INTO COMPLIANCE WITH ROAD DG REQUIREMENT FOR ITS ONWARD GROUND TRANSPORTATION AND FINAL DELIVERY TO THE CONSIGNEE IN THE UK.
column169: IMMEDIATELY FOLLOWING THE CONSIGNEE'S IDENTIFICATION TO EXPEDITORS-PHL OF THE DG, THE SHIPPER WAS CONTACTED FOR AN ACCOUNTING OF THE EVENTS AND CORRECTIVE ACTION. EXPEDITORS AND BOEING PERSONNEL ARE HAVING ON-GOING CONVERSATIONS PERTAINING TO THE ROOT CAUSE OF THIS ISSUE AND MEASURES TO PREVENT REOCCURRENCE.  EXPEDITORS HAVE A VERY ROBUST COMPLIANCE PROGRAM. AS PART OF OUR PROGRAM, ALL EMPLOYEES GLOBALLY ARE REQUIRED TO TAKE GENERAL DG AWARENESS TRAINING ANNUALLY TO IDENTIFY POTENTIALLY HIDDEN OR UNDECLARED DG. AS A REMEDIAL ACTION, EXPEDITORS WILL IMPLEMENT A SECONDARY REVIEW FOR ALL BOEING SHIPMENTS AT EXPEDITORS-PHL UNTIL FURTHER NOTICE. THIS SECONDARY REVIEW PROCESS WILL ENSURE THAT AT LEAST TWO EXPEDITORS-PHL STAFF MEMBERS HAVE THE OPPORTUNITY TO IDENTIFY POTENTIALLY UNDECLARED DG AND WILL OBTAIN ADDITIONAL VERIFICATION AS TO THE DG STATUS OF BOEING SHIPMENTS.  IF ANYTHING FURTHER IS NEEDED, PLEASE LET US KNOW AND IT WILL BE PROMPTLY PROVIDED.

column168: Driver arrived to off load, and upon opening external discharge valve noticed a small leak. Internal and external valves were closed, and driver enacted stop work authority. Driver  notified the receiver he had a small leak, and then notified dispatch of the issue. Dispatch called a road service company (Magnolia Diesel) out to inspect and repair the external discharge valve. Once road service arrived, they found the external valve was missing a gasket, and this mechanic stated he was not trained on a 407 chemical trailer, so a second mechanic was dispatch out that was trained on 407 trailers. The trailer was cleaned and prepped at St. Gabriel Tank Wash. The tank wash employee failed to prep the trailer correctly. Two errors identified, as there was no external valve gasket installed, and the tank wash failed to perform the required vacuum and pressure testing the discharge valve assembly as required. This final step of the prep would have identified the issue of no gasket installed and should have been corrected immediately, then retested to ensure the discharge valve assembly passed the vacuum, and pressure test.  The second mechanic had to get a gasket, install it, then when he put the external valve/clamp back together he failed to properly install external valve clamp. The barrel nut on the clamp was in the wrong position, which allowed the valve to fail when pressure was applied to off load the product.
column169: Failure 1/corrective action - Trailer was not properly cleaned and prepped at tank wash. St Gabriel tank wash has reviewed this major service failure and taken appropriate disciplinary action with the employees involved with this service failure. They have also reviewed this failure of not putting external gasket and not following proper prepping testing and procedures. St Gabriel tank wash put in place additional steps to insure this does not happen again.  Failure 2/ corrective action - The  first road service mechanic admitted  he wasn't trained to repair a 407 chemical trailer, so the process was stopped, and another mechanic (trained on 407 repairs was sent) Failure 3/corrective action - The second mechanic that arrived the next day had previous experience in installing the gasket and the external valve clamp. He failed in installing the wing nut properly as shown in the pictures attached. Magnolia Diesel Services has been made aware of this failure and are taking corrective actions.  Pictures attached Highway Transport corrective action - Safety stand down was conducted and completed with all Highway Managers, dispatchers, mechanics, tank cleaners, and drivers on 11-25-19 This spill/injury is being discussed daily with drivers as a reminder to take full safety precautions and to wear all safety equipment necessary for the unloading of the specified chemical and safety requirements  We are also conducting extra training classes with divers, shop and wash rack technician’s concerning the proper way to connect the external valve wing nut clamp.

column168: DRIVER WAS WESTBOUND ON SUNSHINE RD TURNING ONTO KANSAS HIGHWAY 5. AS DRIVER CAME AROUND THE CORNER HE VEERED OFF THE ROADWAY AND TRAILER ROLLED OVER ON SIDE, EVENTUALLY TURNING OVER IN DITCH ALONGSIDE HIGHWAY 5. WITHIN A FEW MINUTES THE DRIVER HAD REMOVED HIMSELF FROM CAB AND CALLED OUR OFFICE, WHILE ON THE PHONE WITH DISPATCH THE FIRE DEPARTMENT ARRIVED AND IMMEDIATELY PUT BOOMS DOWN TO HELP CONTAIN THE SPILL. ONE COMPARTMENT HAD A SMALL HOLE IN IT AND THE FIRE DEPARTMENT QUICKLY PLUGGED THAT HOLE. ONE THE TOP VENT COVERS WAS ALSO LEAKING SLOWLY EVEN THOUGH IT REMAINED CLOSED. WE CONTACTED THREE CREEKS ENVIRONMENT TO ASSIST WITH THE IMMEDIATE HAZARDOUS MATERIALS RESPONSE AND CLEANUP. THE TRAILER CONTINUED TO LEAK SLOWLY FOR ABOUT 5 HOURS WHILE THE TOW TRUCK COMPANY WORKED TO PUMP REMAINING PRODUCT FROM THE TRAILER INTO ANOTHER TRUCK AND TRAILER. WHEN THE TRAILER WAS EMPTY THE TOW TRUCK COMPANY WAS ABLE TO GET TRUCK AND TRAILER TURNED UPRIGHT AND STOPPED THE LEAKING. WHILE THE TOW TRUCK COMPANY WAS EMPTYING THE TRAILER THREE CREEKS HAS ALREADY STARTED VACUUMING THE DIESEL FUEL THAT HAD BEEN CONTAINED BY THE FIRE DEPARTMENT. AFTER THE INITIAL RESPONSE CLEANUP FROM THREE CREEKS ENVIRONMENT OUT INSURANCE COMPANY FEDERATED INSURANCE TOOK OVER AND HIRED APEX ENVIROTECH TO MANAGE THE CLEANUP RESPONSE.  I HAVE ATTACHED NARRATIVE FROM THREE CREEKS ENVIRONMENTAL AND ALL DOCUMENTATION FROM APEX ENVIROTECH.
column169: THERE HAS BEEN NO DETERMINATION AS TO THE CAUSE OF THE ROLLOVER, ANOTHER TRUCK DRIVER WHO WITNESSED THE ACCIDENT TOLD OUR INSURANCE COMPANY AND THE KANSAS HIGHWAY PATROL THAT HE DID NOT THINK SPEED WAS AN ISSUE IN THE ACCIDENT. column168: ON NOVEMBER 9TH 2019, A SEMI TRUCK OPERATED BY ENERGY DISPATCH, WAS DELIVERING DIESEL FUEL INTO AN UNDER GROUND STORAGE TANK AT RACETRAC LOCATION #243 1975 SW RAILRAOD AVENUE. THE DELIVERY DRIVER FILLED 2 TANKS AT THE LOCATION. BOTH TANKS HAD MORE THAN ENOUGH ULLAGE TO HOLD THE DELIVERED GALLONS ACCORDING TO THE AUTOMATIC TANK GAUGES THAT WERE UTILIZED FOR THIS TRANSFER. FOR UNKNOWN REASONS TANK #2'S TANK GAUGE WAS GIVING INCORRECT INFORMATION, AND SUBSEQUENTLY SAID TANK WAS OVERFILLED. APPROXIMATELY 50 GALLONS OF FUEL LEAKED OUT ONTO THE CONCRETE APRON. THE DELIVERY DRIVER IMMEDIATELY ATTEMPTED TO CONTAIN THE SPILL TO THE IMMEDIATE AREA WITH ABSORBENT PADS, SNAKE AND GRANULAR ABSORBENT MATERIAL. APPROXIMATELY 5 GALLONS OF FUEL DID MANAGE TO LEAK PAST THE DRIVERS EFFORTS TO CONTAIN, AND ENTERED A NEARBY STORM DRAIN CATCH BASIN. ENERGY DISPATCH IMMEDIATELY DISPATCHED A REMEDIATION TEAM TO HANDLE THE CLEAN UP THE FUEL RELEASE.

column168: On November 27, 2019, at approximately 12:15 a.m. CST, R+L Carriers(R+L) personnel observed a punctured five(5) gallon container on a pallet due to improper stacking. As a result of the puncture, the container released approximately one(1) gallon of material to the loading dock concrete floor. On November 27, 2019, at approximately 12:30 a.m. CST, a representative with R+L retained Cura Emergency Services, L.C. (CES) to manage the environmental cleanup on their behalf. Based on the available information the CES incident manger dispatched a crew from Hazmat Special Services (HSS) located in LaPorte, Texas to assess the site and initiate corrective actions. On November 27, 2019, HSS arrived and assessed the site. The crew dawned the appropriate person protective equipment and deployed absorbents to the impacted concrete. HSS utilized hand tools to collected the spent absorbents. The crew collected the damaged packaging and spent absorbents into one(1) 55-gallon drum for transport and disposal. ER secured the site and demobilized.

column168: OUR TRUCK WAS CARRYING PROPANE TANKS CONTAINING RESIDUE RAN INTO SEVERAL VEHICLES ON 1-35W IN DENTON TX. IT APPEARS THAT THE ENSUING FIRE CAUSED BY THE GASOLINE IN THE OTHER VEHICLE'S FUEL TANKS IGNITED A FIRE WHICH FULLY CONTAINED OUR TRUCK. THE STRAPS ON THE TRAILER MELTED ALLOWING TANKS TO FALL OFF ONTO THE ROADWAY. THE HEAT OF THE FIRE CAUSED SOME OF THE POP OFF VALVES TO OPEN WHICH RELEASED RESIDUAL VAPOR WHICH FLARED OUT AS FLAMES. THESE FLAMES CONTRIBUTED TO THE BURNING OF ONE CAR. THE VAPOR CREATED LARGER THAN NORMAL FLAMES DUE TO HEAT OF THE CRASH FIRE BESIDE AND BEHIND THEM. THE POP OFF VALVES DID NOT FAIL BUT WORKED PROPERLY. ONE TANK HAD IT'S SERVICE VALVE SHEARED OFF. I CANNOT CONFIRM THE EXACT TANKS THAT CAUGHT FIRE AS THERE IS AN ONGOING INVESTIGATION WITH THE DENTON POLICE DEPARTMENT. THE FIRE DEPARTMENT WAS ABLE TO CONTAIN THE FLAMES.
column169: UNTIL WE ARE PROVIDED ALL THE DETAILS OF THE ONGOING INVESTIGATION WE ARE UNABLE TO SUGGEST CHANGES OR IMPROVEMENTS.

column168: OUR TRUCK AND TRAILER WAS BEING DRIVEN BY OUR DRIVER ON I-40 EAST AT 3:00 AM HEADED TO CASTILIAN SPRINGS. THE DRIVER RAN OFF THE RIGHT SHOULDER OF THE INTERSTATE AN WAS NOT ABLE TO GET BACK UP ON THE ROADWAY AND ROLLED OVER THE UNIT. THE TANKER SLID DOWN THE ROADWAY AND THE SHELL OF THE TANK RUPTURED CAUSING GASOLINE TO ESCAPE ONTO THE SHOULDER AND RIGHT OF WAY ADJACENT TO THE INTERSTATE.  THE RELEASE LASTED APPROXIMATELY 30 MINUTES AND WAS CONTAINED BY PADS AND BOOMS UNTIL A CLEAN UP CREW ARRIVED WITH A VACUUM TRUCK AT THE SCENE AND STARTED REMOVING THE PRODUCT FROM THE TANKER. THEY THEN PROCEEDED TO CLEAN UP THE GASOLINE FROM THE GROUND.  CLEAN UP OF THE SITE WAS DONE IN THE NEXT 5 DAYS FROM THE ACCIDENT UNTIL ALL WAS REMOVED FROM THE AREA.

column168: OUR OPERATOR WAS APPLYING THE ANHYDROUS TO A CUSTOMERS FIELD. WHILE TURNING THE HOSE BETWEEN THE TANK AND APPLICATOR CAME APART. IT CAME APART IN A MANNER THAT THE EXCESS FLOW VALVE DID NOT CLOSE AS IT SHOULD. THE VAPORS RELEASED TO THE AIR UNTIL THE TANK WAS EMPTY. RELEASE LASTED APPROXIMATELY 35 MINUTES. WHEN RELEASE STARTED THE WIND WAS BLOWING 12 MPH TO THE NORTH AWAY FROM ALL PEOPLE AND BUILDINGS. THERE WAS NO PROBLEMS FOUND WITH THE EQUIPMENT BUT ALL WAS REMOVED FROM SERVICE AND REPLACED WITH NEW.
column169: WE ARE WORKING ON OPERATING PROCEDURES TO MAKE SURE THAT THE HOSE BETWEEN THE TANK AND APPLICATOR CANNOT CATCH ON ANYTHING DURING TURNS.

FOLLOWING A SITE ASSESSMENT, HE PERSONNEL NOTED LESS THAN ONE GALLON OF METHYLENE CHLORIDE WAS RELEASING FROM A 55-GALLON DRUM FROM WHAT APPEARS TO BE DAMAGE FROM A FORKLIFT. R+L PERSONNEL HAD PREVIOUSLY DEPLOYED GRANULAR TO THE AREA OF RELEASE, CONTAINING THE LIQUID TO A SMALL AREA. HE PERSONNEL DEPLOYED ADDITIONAL GRANULAR AND WORKED IT IN USING HANDTOOLS. THE DAMAGED DRUM WAS OVER PACKED IN ONE (1) 55-GALLON METAL DRUM AND ALL METHYLENE CHLORIDE IMPACTED MATERIAL WAS COLLECTED AND CONTAINERIZED IN ONE (1) 30-GALLON POLY DRUM FOR TRANSPORT AND DISPOSAL. column168: ACTION MANUFACTURING COMPANY (ACTION) PRODUCES FUZES AND ORDNANCE PRODUCTS FIR THE U.S. MILITARY. ONE OF OUR MAIN PRODUCTS IS THE M739A1 ARTILLERY FUZE THAT ACTION MAKES FOR THE U.S ARMY. THE M739A1 ARTILLERY FUZE THAT ACTION MAKES FOR THE U.S. ARMY. THE M739A1 FUZE IS INITIALLY ASSEMBLED AT ACTION'S PLANT IN BRISTOL, PA. THE ASSEMBLED M739A1 FUZE AT BRISTOL IS A CLASS 1.4D EXPLOSIVE. AFTER  ASSEMBLY, THE M739A1 FUZE IS SHIPPED TO ACTION'S ATGLEN, PA PLANT WHERE AN EXPLOSIVE BOOSTER IS ADDED. THE BOOSTERED M739A1 IS A CLASS 1.2D EXPLOSIVE. A COMPANY OWNED TRUCK IS USED TO TRANSPORT MATERIAL BETWEEN ACTION'S BRISTOL AND ATGLEN PLANTS.  ACTION IS PARTICIPATING IN A U.S. ARMY ENGINEERING STUDY TO ENHANCE THE PERFORMANCE OF THE M739A1 FUZE. AS PART OF THE STUDY, THE U.S. ARMY SENT 288 M739A1 FUZES TO ACTION'S ATGEN PLANT FOR DE-BOOSTERING. ON NOVEMBER 12, 2019, BELIEVING THAT ALL THE FUZES HAD BEEN DE-BOOSTERED, ACTION SHIPPED THE 288 M739A1 FUZES, PACKED IN 36 4A STEEL BOXES (SEE PART III QUESTION 27), FROM THE ATGLEN PLANT TO THE BRISTOL PLANT WHERE THE DE-BOOSTERED FUZES WERE TO BE DISASSEMBLED AS PART OF THE STUDY. WHEN ONE OF THE AMMUNITION BOXES CONTAINING THE FUZES WAS OPENED AT THE BRISTOL PLANT, IT WAS DISCOVERED THAT THE 8 FUZES IN THE BOX WERE STILL BOOSTERED. BECAUSE ACTION BELIEVED THAT ALL THE FUZES WERE UNBOOSTERED, THE 288 M739A1 FUZES HAD BEEN SHIPPED FROM ATGLEN TO BRISTOL VIA THE COMPANY TRUCK AND PLACARDED AS 1.4D UNBOOSTERED FUZES, WHEN THE PRESENCE OF THE 8 BOOSTERED FUZES REQUIRED THAT THE SHIPMENT SHOULD HAVE BEEN PLACARDED AS A 1.2D SHIPMENT. PROMPTLY AFTER DISCOVERY, THE 8 BOOSTERED FUZES WERE SHIPPED BACK TO THE ATGLEN PLANT BY COMMON CARRIER AS 1.2D EXPLOSIVES.  PLEASE SEE ATTACHED SHEET FOR CONTINUATION.
column169: M739 A1 FUZE DE-BOOSTERING IS A RARELY PERFORMED OPERATION. CHANGES IN PROCEDURE TO PREVENT RECURRENCE ARE: AMMUNITION BOXES WITH M739A1 FUZES TO BE DE-BOOSTERED WILL BE SET ASIDE ON A SEPARATE SKID. ONLY ONE AMMUNITION BOX AT A TIME WILL BE TAKEN TO THE DE-BOOSTERING WORK STATION. ANY TIME AN OPERATOR LEAVES THE WORK STATION, ALL FUZES FROM EACH AMMUNITION BOX MUST BE DE-BOOSTERED AND THE STATION CLEARED. AFTER DE-BOOSTERING, THE FUZES WILL BE REPACKED IN THE AMMUNITION BOX AND MOVED TO A SEPARATE SKID DESIGNATED AS "COMPLETED UNBOOSTERED FUZES." AT THE END OF THE DE-BOOSTERING JOB, THE SUPERVISOR OVERSEEING THE OPERATION WILL 100% INSPECT THE FUZES. THE INSPECTION WILL INCLUDE A 100% COUNT OF THE NUMBER OF DE-BOOSTERED FUZES WITH A COUNT OF BOOSTER PELLETS TO BE SURE THE NUMBERS MATCH. THE INSPECTION WILL BE COMPLETED PRIOR TO THE SKID BEING TRANSFERRED TO THE PLANT WAREHOUSE. THE SUPERVISOR WILL COMPLETE THE SHOP TRAVELER TAG CONFIRMING THE TOTAL QUANTITY OF DE-BOOSTERED FUZES.

column168: THE WASTE ARRIVED AT INGENIUM'S EXEMPT 10 DAY TRANSFER STATION ON 11/19/2019. THERE WAS LEAK OR STRAY LIQUIDS FOUND ANYWHERE ON THE DRUM OR NEAR THE OPEN TOP SEAL.  OUR INVESTIGATION DETERMINED THE SPILL WAS LIKELY A CAUSE OF WEAR AND TEAR ON THE DRUM LEADING TO THE DRUM'S MANUFACTURED SEAL OPENING ENOUGH TO RELEASE.

column168: ON NOVEMBER 25, 2019, WHILE PERFORMING THE MORNING RAIL-CAR REPORT OF HERITAGE TRANSPORT, LLC (HT) CARS ON THE SERVICE TRACK ASSIGNED TO HT AT THE INDIANA RAILROAD (INRD), THE HT RAIL YARD OPERATOR, OBSERVED THE SWING GATE SECUREMENT CHAINS ON CONTAINER ESDU 0084 WERE BROKEN AND THE GATE WAS CRACKED OPEN. THE INTER-MODAL CONTAINER (EDSU 0084) WAS LOADED IN NEW JERSEY AND SHIPPED TO INRD FOR OFFLOADING AND TRANSPORT TO THE INTENDED DESTINATION. THE RAIL YARD OPERATOR OBSERVED THAT CONTAMINATED SOIL MATERIAL WAS RELEASED OUT ONTO THE TARP AND IN BETWEEN THE INTER-MODAL BOXES (HESU 48568, MJVU 1015) BELOW ESDU 0084. THE RAIL YARD OPERATOR IMMEDIATELY NOTIFIED MANAGEMENT.  TWO HT EMPLOYEES WERE DISPATCHED TO THE INRD TO INVESTIGATE AND INITIATE A CLEANUP AND RECOVERY PLAN. THEY TOOK PICTURES OF MATERIAL RELEASED FROM THE INTERMODAL CONTAINER AND TRAPPED ON TOP, IN BETWEEN, AND ON THE RAILCAR. THERE WAS NO CONTAMINATED SOIL OBSERVED ON THE RAIL BALLAST OR GROUND. TARPS WERE PLACED UNDER THE CONTAINER TO COLLECT ANY MATERIAL THAT MAY FALL OFF THE CONTAINER OR RAILCAR DURING CLEAN UP. THE TAILGATE ON ESDU 0084 WAS SECURED WITH NEW CHAINS AND BINDERS, THEN ESDU 0084 WAS REMOVED FROM THE RAILCAR.  LOOSE MATERIAL WAS COLLECTED BETWEEN LOWER BOTTOM CONTAINERS, FROM THE TOP OF CONTAINERS TARPS, AND OFF THE RAILCAR AND RETURNED TO THE ORIGINAL INTERMODAL CONTAINER. THE TARPS THAT HAD BEEN PLACED UNDER THE RAILCAR AS CONTAINMENT WERE ROLLED WITH ANY LOOSE MATERIAL AND PLACED INTO THE ORIGINAL CONTAINER ESDU 0084. APPROXIMATELY 4 HOURS ELAPSED BETWEEN THE TIME THE RELEASE WAS NOTICED AND THE CLEAN UP WAS COMPLETE.  DURING THE CLEANUP, IT WAS NOTED THE LEAD CAR ON THE SERVICE TRACK ASSIGNED TO HT HAD A BROKEN HINGE PIN ON THE KNUCKLE. HT IDENTIFIED A PORTION OF THE OLD KNUCKLE PIN REMAINED IN THE KNUCKLE, AND HT REPRESENTATIVES OBSERVED THAT A NEW PIN WAS INSTALLED ON TOP OF THE OLD PIN. AS A RESULT, APPROXIMATELY HALF OF THE NEW PIN WAS STICKING UP ABOVE THE KNUCKLE AND NOT SECURED. IT IS UNKNOWN WHERE OR WHEN THE CHAINS BROKE ON THE INTERMODAL CONTAINER, BUT IT APPEARS THAT DURING THE COURSE OF THE SHIPMENT THE CARS MAY HAVE HUMPED TOO HARD OR BEEN HIT BY ANOTHER CAR USING AN ENGINE WHICH CAUSED THE CHAINS TO BREAK ON INTERMODAL CONTAINER.  HT VISUAL INSPECTION RECORDS INDICATE THE CONTAINER DID NOT HAVE ANY DEFECTS WHEN SHIPPED EMPTY OR LOADED BY RAIL OR TRUCK UNTIL IT WAS OBSERVED THE CHAINS WERE BROKEN AFTER THE CAR HAD BEEN PLACED IN THE INRD YARD IN INDIANAPOLIS. THE EMPTY INTERMODAL CONTAINER WAS VISUALLY INSPECTED WHEN IT LEFT THE RAILYARD IN BRIDGEPORT, NJ TO GO TO THE CUSTOMER'S SITE FOR LOADING. EACH INTER-MODAL CONTAINER WAS ALSO INSPECTED BEFORE AND AFTER LOADING AT THE CUSTOMER SITE, AS WELL AS WHEN IT WAS PLACED ON THE RAILCAR IN BRIDGEPORT, NJ FOR SHIPMENT.  PHOTOGRAPHS ARE PROVIDED OF THE CONTAINER, RAILCAR, AND RELEASED MATERIALS BEFORE AND AFTER IT WAS CLEANED UP.

column168: On November 25, 2019, at approximately 02:30 a.m. CDT, a tractor-trailer(SF2170) parked at dock door 22 at the above-referenced location when an employee accidentally punctured the container with forks from the forklift. As a result of the impact, the container was damaged and released approximately 2.5 gallons of UN1263 to the trailer floor. At approximately 03:33 a.m.,/ CDT, a representative from R+L Carriers retained Cura Emergency Services, L.C.(CES) to manage the environmental remediation of the site on their behalf. Based on the available information, the CES incident manager dispatched a crew from ACV Environmental to assess and remediate the site as necessary. At approximately 07:50 a.m. CDT, a crew from ACV Enviro arrived on-site. Following a site assessment, ACV personnel noted approximately 2.5 gallons of UN1263(paint related materials) released to the trailer floor. ACV personnel deployed absorbent pads. All paint related impacted material was collected and containerized in one(1) 55-gallon 1 metal drum and two(2) 55-gallon poly drums for transport and disposal. ACV personnel noted no further actions required on-site.

column168: DRIVER OF VEHICLE APPEARED TO FALL ASLEEP AND DRIFTED OFF THE ROADWAY AT APPROX 35 MPH. VEHICLE EVENT RECORDER CAPTURED THE EVENT. ROAD HAD STEEP DROP OFF AND AS THE VEHICLE WENT OFF THE ROAD IMMEDIATELY BEGAN TO TILT TO THE RIGHT AND ROLLED ON ITS SIDE. VEHICLE TRAVELED FOR APPROXIMATELY 15 YARDS BEFORE COMING TO A STOP. TRAILER, WHICH WAS LOADED WITH 198BBLS, SUFFERED A PUNCTURE, RESULTING IN THE RELEASE OF APPROXIMATELY 50 BBLS.
column169: IMMEDIATELY AFTER THE EVENT, WE DID A STAND-DOWN WITH OUT FLEET TO TALK ABOUT THE INCIDENT. EMPLOYEES WERE ENCOURAGED TO NOTIFY US IN THE EVENT THEY FELT FATIGUE OR ILL. WE HAVE ALSO RETRAINED ALL EMPLOYEES ON FATIGUE MANAGEMENT IN AN EFFORT TO HELP THEM RECOGNIZE SYMPTOMS OF SLEEPINESS/FATIGUE AND HOW TO AVOID THEM.

column168: THE INCIDENT WAS A SINGLE VEHICLE INCIDENT INVOLVING OIL RECOVERY COMPANY "ORC" TRUCK 109, A BOX TRUCK CARRYING 600 GALLONS OF UN 1824 SODIUM HYDROXIDE IN 2 STAINLESS STEEL TOTES. THE ORC DRIVER WAS MAKING A RIGHT HAND TURN OFF OF DUNLAP DR. ONTO ADDSCO RD. WHEN THE TRUCK ROLLED OVER. ACCORDING TO THE DATA RETRIEVED FROM THE GPS TRACKING SYSTEM THERE WAS HARSH CORNERING AND BREAKING IMMEDIATELY BEFORE THE FINAL HARSH CORNERING THAT RESULTED IN THE ROLL OVER AND SPILLAGE OF THE SODIUM HYDROXIDE.  THE ORC SPILL RESPONSE TEAM WAS ACTIVATED AND RESPONDED IMMEDIATELY TO THE SPILL OF SODIUM HYDROXIDE. THE SPILL WAS CONTAINED, CLEANED UP AND THE ENVIRONMENT WAS REMEDIATED COMPLETELY. THE REMAINING SODIUM HYDROXIDE IN THE CONTAINERS WAS REMOVED PRIOR TO TRUCK BEING TOWED TO ORC FACILITY.

column168: THE DELIVERY DRIVER WAS TRAVELING ON RURAL ROAD TO MAKE A PROPANE DELIVERY. ROADS WERE WET FROM THE STORM THE NIGHT BEFORE AND TEMPERATURE WERE FALLING. AS DRIVER CRESTED THE SUNNY SIDE OF THE HILL WHERE THE PAVEMENT WAS EXPOSED TO THE SUN AND WET, THE OTHER SIDE OF THE HILL WAS SHADED WHERE HE ENCOUNTERED BLACK ICE AND LOST TRACTION. THE TRUCK SLID TO THE LEFT CROSSING THE CENTERLINE SIDEWAYS. AS THE DRIVE TIRES HIT THE COMPACT GRAVEL AT THE EDGE OF THE ROAD, THE TRUCK OVERTURNED AND CAME TO REST UPSIDE DOWN. DRIVER WAS SHAKEN FROM EVENT. WE SENT HIM VIA AMBULANCE TO ER TO BE CHECKED AND OBSERVED. DRIVER SUFFERED MINOR INJURIES AND WAS BACK ON DUTY THE NEXT DAY.
column169: WHEN WE FOUND OUT ABOUT THIS INCIDENT, WE PUT AN ALERT OUT COMPANY-WIDE, WARNING DRIVERS AND TECHNICIANS OF THE POTENTIAL FOR BLACK ICE CONDITIONS DUE TO CHANGING ENVIRONMENTAL CONDITIONS.

column168: WHEN THE DRIVER ARRIVED AT THE STATION, HE AND THE MANAGER WERE UNABLE TO LOCATED A 2ND  UNLEADED TANK DUE TO SNOW COVERING THE LOT. THE STORE MANAGER ASKED HER MANAGER, WHO TOLD HER THAT OUR DRIVER COULD UNLOAD HIS ENTIRE DELIVERY INTO THE ONE TANK AND IT WOULD EQUALIZE INTO THE OTHER TANK AS HE UNLOADED. WHEN THE DRIVER WAS UNLOADING INTO THE TANK, IT BECAME FULL AND THE PRODUCT CAME OUT OF THE TANK ONTO THE PARKING AREA, AND DOWN INTO A STORM DRAIN. THE GASOLINE WAS FORCED OUT OF THE TANK FROM A FITTING ON THE OTHER END OF THE TANK, WHERE THE TANK GAUGE SYSTEM IS. THE DRIVER IMMEDIATELY NOTICED PRODUCT COMING OUT OF THE THE TANK GAUGE END OF THE TANK, SHUTT OFF HIS DELIVERY, AND CONTACTED MANAGEMENT AND AUTHORITIES.
column169: RECOMMENDATIONS  1. THE STATION MANAGER NEEDS TO BE TRAINED IN THEIR SITE EQUIPMENT/SETUP, WHICH IS REQUIRED BY COLORADO OIL AND PUBLIC SAFETY REGULATIONS. 2. THE TANK OVERFILL SHUTT OFF NEEDS TO BE REPAIRED, WHICH WOULD HAVE SHUTT OFF THE DELIVERY BEFORE THE SPILL COULD OCCUR, WHEN THE TANK LEVEL REACHED 90% FULL (THIS IS ALSO REQUIRED BY COLORADO OIL AND PUBLIC SAFETY) 3. column168: MIKE SMITH WAS APPLYING ANHYDROUS AMMONIA IN A FIELD LOCATED ON THE WEST SIDE OF 355TH ST. ON THE SOUTHSIDE OF THE RAILROAD TRACKS AND 1/3 OF A MILE SOUTH OF IL ROUTE 96. WHILE APPLYING THE AMMONIA IN THE FIELD BOLTS ON THE TOOLBAR BROKE CAUSING THE HITCH ON THE TOOLBAR TO BREAK LOOSE. THIS THEN CAUSED THE AMMONIA NURSE WAGON THAT WAS BEING PULLED TO COME TO A STOP, BEFORE THE TRACTOR COULD STOP THE HOSE THAT CONNECTED THE TOOLBAR TO THE ANHYDROUS AMMONIA TANKS STRETCHED AND TORE APART CAUSING AMMONIA TO RELEASE FROM THE TWO 1,000 GALLONS TANKS ON THE WAGON INTO THE ATMOSPHERE.  THE PLEASANT HILL FIRE DEPARTMENT WAS IMMEDIATELY NOTIFIED OF THE RELEASE. THE NATIONAL RESPONSE  CENTER AND THE ILLINOIS EMERGENCY MANAGEMENT AGENCY WERE ALSO NOTIFIED OF THE RELEASE. THE WIND WAS BLOWING OUT OF THE NORTHWEST AT 8MPH. THE PLEASANT HILL SCHOOL WAS LOCATED NORTH OF THE RELEASE APPROXIMATELY 1/3 MILE AND THEY WERE NOTIFIED OF THE RELEASE SO THEY COULD BE ON ALERT STATUS.  IT WAS DETERMINED BY THE FIRE DEPARTMENT THAT THE WAGON COULD NOT BE SAFELY APPROACHED TO ATTEMPT TO SHUT OFF THE VALVES TO STOP THE RELEASE. THE AMMONIA WAS BLOWING ACROSS UNINHABITED CROPLAND WITH THE MAJORITY OF THE AMMONIA DISSIPATING UP INTO THE ATMOSPHERE. THERE WERE NO FACILITIES, INJURIES, EVACUATIONS, SHELTER-IN-PLACE OR ENVIRONMENTAL DAMAGE AS A RESULT OF THIS RELEASE.
column169: THE BOLTS ON THE TOOLBAR THAT BROKE HAVE BEEN REPLACED AND THEY WILL BE INSPECTED ON A ROUTINE BASIS TO INSURE THAT THEY ARE IN SOUND CONDITION.

DRIVER NOTIFIED POLICE AND FIRE DEPARTMENT WHO CAME TO THE SCENE AND CONTAINED THE SPILL. WHICH WAS FOLLOWED BY CLEAN UP CREW WHICH WAS HIRED BY THE EPA. HAYDER CAMARGO FROM THE STATE OF NEW JERSEY DEP WAS THE INDIVIDUAL WHO CALLED IN THE CLEAN UP CREW. HE IS AN EMERGENCY RESPONSE SPECIALIST FOR THE BUREAU OF EMERGENCY  RESPONSE. HIS PHONE NUMBER IS 973-631-6351. AT FIRST IT WAS BELIEVED THE SPILL WAS ROUGHLY AROUND 3000 GALLONS. AFTERWARDS IT WAS DEEMED TO BE 1476 GALLONS.

column168: THE TANK WAS RECEIVED AT THE NOVO NORDISK FACILITY AND CONTAINER INTEGRITY VERIFIED VISUALLY. IT WAS TRANSFERRED TO THE SAMPLING AREA WHERE IT WAS FOUND TO BE UNDER A SLIGHT VACUUM. THE CONTENTS WERE SUBSEQUENTLY VISUALLY VERIFIED BY OPENING A MANWAY. THE CONTAINER WAS THEN TRANSFERRED TO THE CHEMICAL UNLOADING AREA FOR OFFLOAD DESIGNED AND CONSTRUCTED TO CONTAIN THE FULL CONTENTS OF THE TANKER SHOULD LEAKS OCCUR. THE TANK IS CONSTRUCTED IN A MANNER WHEREAS MATERIALS CAN ONLY BE REMOVED VIA USE OF A DRY DIP TUBE. PRESSURE IS APPLIED TO THE HEAD SPACE AND MATERIALS ARE PUSHED OUT THE DIP TUBE TO THE RECEIVING PIPING. DURING STANDARD LEAK TEST PROCEDURES , A SMALL AMOUNT OF PRESSURE IS APPLIED TO THE VESSEL DURING WHICH TIME A SMALL AMOUNT OF MATERIAL, ESTIMATED TO BE LESS THAN 10 GALLONS, SLOWLY LEAKED OUT OF THE AREA BETWEEN THE DIP TUBE AND VALVE ASSEMBLY ON THE CONTAINER. AS THE INCIDENT OCCURRED DURING HUMID CONDITIONS, AIR MOISTURE REACTED WITH THE NITRIC ACID AND A VAPOR WAS VISIBLE  TO PERSONNEL. THE TEAM MONITORING THE EVOLUTION CONSERVATIVELY EVACUATED PERSONNEL FROM THE IMMEDIATE AREA. THE ON-SITE EMERGENCY RESPONSE TEAM WAS ALREADY ENGAGED AND ONSITE AS PART OF PRE-PLANNING ALONG WITH LOCAL EMERGENCY RESPONDERS AND AS SUCH WERE IMMEDIATELY AWARE OF THE INCIDENT. WHILE ADDITIONAL COUNTY EMERGENCY RESPONDERS DID ARRIVE ON-SITE AS A PRECAUTION, THEY PROVIDED AN OVERSIGHT OF ACTIVITIES AND WERE NOT INVOLVED IN THE RESPONSE OR CLEAN-UP. SHORTLY AFTER LEAKAGE STARTED AND CONFIRMED DURING POST INCIDENT INVESTIGATION, IT WAS FOUND THAT NO GASKET HAD BEEN INSTALLED HAD BEEN INSTALLED FORM THE SUPPLIER BETWEEN THE DIP TUBE INSTALLED ON THE VESSEL AND THE CONTROL VALVE. FURTHERMORE, THE VALVE WAS FOUND TO BE LOOSELY SECURED TO THE VESSEL. A GASKET WAS INSTALLED, AND BOLTS TIGHTENED TO FACILITATE FULL UNLOADING WHICH WAS COMPLETED. DURING THE SHIPMENT TO THE FACILITY IT IS BELIEVED NO MATERIAL COULD HAVE LEAKED AS THE VESSEL WAS UNDER A VACUUM AND SEALED. WHEN THIS VACUUM WAS REMOVED DURING THE RECEIPT PROCESS, THE FAILURE MODE OCCURRED. UNDER NORMAL SHIPPING CONDITIONS THIS VESSEL WOULD NOT BE EXPECTED TO BE RECEIVED UNDER VACUUM.
column169: 1. VISUALLY INSPECTED THE CONTAINER THOROUGHLY BEFORE USE 2. CHECK ALL FLANGES AND FITTINGS USED IN THE TRANSFER PROCESS PRIOR TO USE.

column168: DRIVER, MICHAEL MORROW, OF SCHNEIDER INDUSTRIES WAS DELIVERING PRODUCT UNDER ACTIVE SHIPPING PAPERS TO AMREX CHEMICAL CO INC SITE. SHIPPER WAS MEGALOID LABORATORIES. DRIVER HAD TO STOP OUTSIDE OF THE FACILITY SECURITY GATE FOR CLEARANCE. AT THAT TIME, HE OPENED THE HATCH FOR AN EMPLOYEE TO INSPECT THE  PRODUCT TO VERIFY IT WAS CLEAR. HE THEN GOT BACK IN HIS VEHICLE AND FAILED TO JUDGE PROPER CLEARANCE AND DROVE INTO THE FACILITY GATE/FENCE. AT THIS TIME, PRODUCT WAS SPILLED FROM THE HATCH THAT HE FAILED TO SECURE. THE PRODUCT, METHYL ETHYL KETONE, WAS STILL IN THE CONTROL OF THE DRIVER OF SCHNEIDER INDUSTRIES AND HAD NOT BEEN DELIVERED OR SIGNED FOR BY AMREX CHEMICAL CO. PERSONNEL.  MEGALOID INDUSTRIES WAS NOTIFIED AND THE COMPANY AND THEIR INSURANCE ARE PAYING FOR THE COSTS OF DISPOSAL OF THE SPILLED PRODUCT AS WELL AS THE REPAIRS TO THE GATE AND FENCE. THE SPILL AND DAMAGE WAS IN NO WAY THE FAULT OF AMREX CHEMICAL CO INC  THIS REPORT IS BEING FILED BY AMREX CHEMICAL CO. INC PER CORRESPONDENCE DATED 2/3/20. A REPORT WAS NOT  FILED AT THE TIME OF THE INCIDENT AS AMREX CHEMICAL CO. INC. WAS NOT IN PHYSICAL POSSESSION OF THE HAZARDOUS MATERIAL IN QUESTION AT THE TIME OF THE INCIDENT. THE INCIDENT OCCURRED PRIOR TO UNLOADING OF THE PRODUCT WHILE IT WAS STILL IN TRANSIT BY SCHNEIDER INDUSTRIES FOR MEGALOID INDUSTRIES.
column169: SCHNEIDER DRIVER, MICHAEL MORROW, NEEDS TRAINING ON HOW TO SECURE HIS LOAD AS WELL AS HOW TO PROPERLY DRIVE THROUGH A SECURITY GATE.  NYS POLICE ACCIDENT REPORT SHOWED THE SCHNEIDER DRIVER WAS AT FAULT.

On November 11, 2019, at approximately 5:05 pm CDT, Landstar personnel noticed a leak coming from a trailer at the above-referenced location due to a faulty valve. cap. As a result, approximately 10 gallons of Flotron JM201A(Xylene, Ethylbenzene mixture was released to the trailer floor and concrete surface below. At approximately 7:02 am CDT, a representative from Lanstar retained Cura Emergency Services, LC CES to manage the environmental remediation of the site on their behalf. Based on the available information, the CES incident manager dispatched a crew from E3 Enhanced Environmental (E3) to assess and remediate the sire as necessary. At approximately 9:45 am CDT, a crew from E3 arrived on-site. Following a site assessment, E3 personnel noted approximately 10 gallons of Xylene, Ethylbenzene released to the trailer floor, further migrating to the concrete surface below. The cause of the leak was found to be a faulty cap on the valve. Crews utilized a fork lift to remove the tote from the trailer. Once removed, E3 personnel transferred the contents from the faulty tote into a new tote. Crew then deployed hydrocarbon appetite microbial agent to the trailer concrete surface below. E3 personnel utilized absorbent pad to wipe the trailer floor and remaining totes that were impacted. All Xylene, ethylbenzene impacted material was collected and contalnerized In one(1) 55-gallon drum, as well as the faulty tote, for transport and disposal. E3 Personnel noted no further actions were required on-site and crews demobilized.
column169: Following the corrective actions, no visual or olfactory evidence of the Xylene, Ethylbenzene could be observed at the site. Based on these results, it api that the corrective actions were successful, and no further action should be required. CES recommends this incident be closed.
